&gt; No, I don&#39;t think it&#39;s a bug. Further down in the same method body
&gt; it resolves the class:
&gt;
&gt; if (resolve)
&gt; resolveClass(c);
&gt; return c;
&gt;
&gt; The method wants to check to see if the class should be
&gt; excluded before loading and resolving it. Otherwise, other classes
&gt; that the class depends upon might be loaded, but which cannot
&gt; be unloaded if the class is subsequently excluded by JUnit&#39;s class
&gt; exclusion list.
&gt;
&gt; &lt;off-topic&gt;
&gt; If you really want to write your own JUnit class loader I would
&gt; recommend that you write it from scratch, and create an implementation
&gt; that only overrides ClassLoader.findClass(String name), specifying
&gt; the classes you want to include rather than classes you want to exclude.
&gt; Keep the system CLASSPATH set to just the classes you need for your test
&gt; runner and nothing else. This would align your class loader to Sun
&gt; recommendations on such things. I don&#39;t know why JUnit&#39;s class loading
&gt; is written the way it is, perhaps someone could enlighten me, but I
&gt; expect it is because the code pre-dates JDK 1.2, when the Java class
&gt; loading model was no as stable.
&gt; &lt;/off-topic&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Malcolm
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; On Sun, 2003-09-14 at 22:33, David Vydra wrote:
&gt; &gt; I was writing a reloading console runner and had to make the following
&gt; &gt; change in order to make it work. Is this a known bug?
&gt; &gt; Thanks
&gt; &gt; David
&gt; &gt; www.testdriven.com
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; public class TestCaseClassLoader extends ClassLoader {
&gt; &gt; ...
&gt; &gt; public synchronized Class loadClass(String name, boolean resolve)
&gt; &gt;   throws ClassNotFoundException {
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;   //Class c= findLoadedClass(name);
&gt; &gt;   //DV original code forgot to resolve here
&gt; &gt;   Class c = super.loadClass(name,resolve);
&gt; &gt;   if (c != null)
&gt; &gt;    return c;
&gt; &gt; ...
